NOTES. V. ii. 37—iii. 47. 175

36. illanc aetatem] i. e. ‘ youth ;' so Bac.111. iii. 5, Minus mirandum est, illaec aetas siquid illorum saed, Quam si nonfacial .· feci ego istaec itidem in adulescentia.

41. neque quicquam succenseo] ‘ nor do I retain any lurking grudge on any accounts so Bae.111. iv. 27, Eadem exorabo, Chrusalo causa mea Pater ne noceat, neu quid ei succenseat; and in IV. iv. 39 Mnesilochus assures Chrysalus that he had prevailed upon his father. . . libi ne noceat, nen quid ob eam rem succenseat. The full construction is suc- censere alicui aliquid or ob aliquam rem, but it is frequently used with one case only, or without a case, and frequently signifies simply ‘to be angry.' Thus As. Ι. ii. 20, ΙΙ. ii. 87, 105, iv. 53; Bac. III. vi. 4; Capt. III. v, 11, 22, V. i. 23; Men. V. vii. 58; Mere. II. ii. 46, V. iii. 15, iv. 52; Mil. III. i. 102 ; Pers. III. iii. 26; Poen. Ι. ii. 157; Pseud. Ι. ν. 56, 573 Stich. IV. ii. 20; Trin. V. ii. 40, 42, 60; Truc. V. 6.

47. Tranioni remitte, quaeso, hanc noxiam] Cf. Poen. I. ii. 191, Verum eliam tibi hanc amittam noxiam unam, Agorastocles, IVon sum irata.
